<body>

<h1>SafeHer - Mobile App Build Guide (Android APK)</h1>
<p>The SafeHer frontend has <strong>Capacitor</strong> already integrated, which wraps the React web application into a native Android shell. Follow these steps to build your Android mobile application (<code>.apk</code>) file.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>🛠️ Step 1: Install Prerequisites</h2>
<p>To build the app, ensure you have the following installed on your computer:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Android Studio</strong>: Download and install from <a href="https://developer.android.com/studio">developer.android.com/studio</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Node.js</strong>: (Already installed on your system).</li>
</ul>

<hr/>

<h2>💻 Step 2: Build and Sync Web Assets</h2>
<p>Before building the mobile application package, you must compile the latest frontend source code:</p>

<ol>
    <li>Open your terminal and navigate to the <strong><code>frontend</code></strong> directory:
        <pre>cd frontend</pre>
    </li>
    <li>Compile the production build of the React application assets:
        <pre>node node_modules/vite/bin/vite.js build</pre>
        <p><em>(This creates your compiled website code in the <code>dist/</code> folder)</em></p>
    </li>
    <li>Sync these compiled assets to the native Android project:
        <pre>npx cap sync</pre>
        <p><em>(This copies the files from <code>dist/</code> to the Android app assets folder)</em></p>
    </li>
</ol>

<hr/>

<h2>🤖 Step 3: Compile the APK in Android Studio</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Open the Android project in Android Studio automatically from your terminal:
        <pre>npx cap open android</pre>
        <p><em>(Alternatively, you can open Android Studio manually, click "Open Project", and select the <code>women-safety/frontend/android</code> folder)</em></p>
    </li>
    <li><strong>Wait for Gradle Sync</strong>: When Android Studio opens, wait for the background Gradle build task to finish sync (you will see progress bars at the bottom right).</li>
    <li><strong>Build the APK File</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>In the top menu bar of Android Studio, click: <strong>Build</strong> -> <strong>Build Bundle(s) / APK(s)</strong> -> <strong>Build APK(s)</strong>.</li>
            <li>Android Studio will compile the code.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li><strong>Locate the Completed APK File</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>Once compilation completes, a popup notification will appear in the bottom-right corner stating: <code>APK(s) generated successfully for 1 module</code>.</li>
            <li>Click the blue <strong>locate</strong> link inside that popup.</li>
            <li>This opens the output folder containing your installable file: <strong><code>app-debug.apk</code></strong>.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ol>

<hr/>

<h2>📱 Step 4: Install on Your Mobile Device</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Transfer the compiled <strong><code>app-debug.apk</code></strong> file to your Android phone (via USB cable, Bluetooth, email, or Google Drive).</li>
    <li>Tap the file on your phone to install it.</li>
    <li>If prompted, enable "Install from Unknown Sources" in your phone's security settings.</li>
    <li>Launch the <strong>SafeHer</strong> app directly from your mobile home screen!</li>
</ol>

</body>
